ceased","1185–1234":"1185–1234","1208–Male":"1208–Deceased","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1213–Female":"1213–Deceased","–1222":"–1222","1157–Male":"1157–Deceased","minor 1222":"1222","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1180":"1180","1204":"1204","about 1208":"about 1208","1215":"1215","1213":"1213","1224":"1224","about 1207":"about 1207","1157":"1157","1267":"1267","1234":"1234","Abt 1210":"about 1210","1222":"1222","1210":"1210","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, France":"Coulaine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France","North Lees Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Lees, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marc","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Aurele, Alexandre, Edeline, Lucien, Lucner, Mireille, Pierrot, Renald, Rochenel.","French, Haitian, and Romanian: from the personal name <i>Marc</i> (see   Mark  ).","Breton (mainly Finistère; also <b>Le Marc</b>): from the personal name <i>Marc'h</i>, from Breton <i>marc'h</i> ‘horse’, and probably also from the (French) personal name <i>Marc</i>, which is of Latin origin (see 1 and   Mark  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Marquet","meanings":["French:","habitational name from (Le) Marquet, the name of several places in various parts of France.","from <i>Marquet</i>, a derivative of the personal name   Marc  . It is also found in Germany."]},{"name":"Mark","meanings":["English, Dutch, and Sorbian: from Latin <i>Marcus</i>, the personal name of Saint Mark the Evangelist, author of the second Gospel in the New Testament. This name was also borne by a number of early Christian saints. <i>Marcus</i> is an ancient Roman name, of uncertain (possibly non-Italic) etymology; it may have some connection with the name of the war god <i>Mars</i>; compare   Martin  . The personal name was not as popular in England in the Middle Ages as it was elsewhere in Europe, especially in Italy, where the evangelist became the patron of Venice and the Venetian Republic. He was allegedly buried at Aquileia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates and similar-sounding names from other languages, e.g. Polish, Czech, and Slovak   Marek  , Ukrainian, Slovenian, Sorbian, Rusyn, and Croatian   Marko  , Greek   Markos  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Jewish and Slavic   Markowicz   and   Markovich  ; see also 6 below.","English and German; Dutch (<b>Van der Mark</b>): topographic name for someone who lived on a boundary between two districts, from Middle English <i>merke</i>, Middle High German <i>marc</i>, Middle Dutch <i>marke</i>, <i>merke</i>, all meaning ‘borderland’. The German term also denotes an area of fenced-off land (see   Marker   5) and, like the English word, is embodied in various placenames which have given rise to habitational names. This surname (in any of the possible senses; see also 5 below) is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine; compare   Marck  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Marck, Pas-de-Calais, France."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Philip Marc Sheriff of Nottingham was born in 1180, in Coulaine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France as the son of Mr. Marc. He married Aline of Somerset about 1207, in Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. In 1209, at the age of 29, his occupation is listed as high sheriff of derbyshire in Derbyshire, England. He died in 1229, in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1180–1229":"1180–1229","1183–Male":"1183–Surnud","1185–1234":"1185–1234","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","–1222":"–1222","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","minor 1222":"1222","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1180":"1180","1204":"1204","about 1208":"umbes 1208","1215":"1215","1213":"1213","1224":"1224","about 1207":"umbes 1207","1157":"1157","1267":"1267","1234":"1234","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1222":"1222","1210":"1210","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, France":"Coulaine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Prantsusmaa","North Lees Hall, Derbyshire, England":"Lees, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Nottingham, Nottingha